        "narrative_summary": "The ATM c.829G>T substitution creates a premature stop codon at glutamate 277 (p.Glu277*), truncating the protein early in its kinase domain. This loss‑of‑function change has been reported in patients with ataxia‑telangiectasia (A‑T) and in cancer cohorts, indicating a link to both the classic A‑T phenotype and cancer predisposition.\n\nClinical observations describe a homozygous stop‑gain c.829G>T in an Iranian individual with classic A‑T features, confirmed by Sanger sequencing and classified as pathogenic in the study’s diagnostic workflow [32962506]. The same variant appears in a curated list of germline pathogenic ATM alleles associated with an increased lymphoma risk (odds ratio ≈ 2.6) [PMC9633290] and is reported homozygously in another A‑T patient investigated for class‑switch recombination defects, where it was also designated pathogenic [PMC8821084]. An autoimmunity survey of monogenic combined immune deficiencies lists the variant among ATM mutations without further comment, confirming its presence in affected individuals [PMC9760934].\n\nFunctional assessment includes structural modelling of the truncated ATM protein using SWISS‑MODEL, which predicts loss of critical functional domains, supporting a deleterious effect of the variant [32962506]. In a cancer‑genome mining study, the c.829G>T allele is annotated as a likely oncogenic nonsense mutation in uterine endometrioid carcinoma, reinforcing its potential role in tumorigenesis [PMC7979806].\n\nPopulation data show the allele is essentially absent from large reference cohorts, with reported frequencies of 0.00000 and a low value of 0.00133 in the supplementary germline variant table, consistent with a rare, disease‑associated mutation [PMC9633290]. No explicit in‑silico predictive scores are provided in the extracted evidence.\n\nCollectively, the evidence converges on a pathogenic classification for ATM c.829G>T. Multiple independent clinical reports associate the variant with A‑T and cancer risk, functional modelling predicts loss of ATM activity, and population databases indicate extreme rarity. No contradictory findings are presented, leading to the conclusion that c.829G>T is a pathogenic, loss‑of‑function allele in ATM.",
        "structured_summary": {
            "overall_pathogenicity": "pathogenic",
            "pathogenicity_counts": {
                "supports pathogenicity": 4,
                "uncertain": 0,
                "supports benignity": 0
            },
            "conflicting_evidence": false
        },
        "article_mentions": [
            {
                "mentions": [
                    {
                        "quoted_text": "INTRODUCTION: Ataxia telangiectasia (A-T) is a rare autosomal recessive, multisystemic disease. Patients with the A-T syndrome present a broad spectrum of disease phenotypes. The ATM (ataxia telangiectasia mutated) gene, the only causative gene for A-T. METHOD: A patient of Persian origin presenting with typical A-T was referred to our genetics centre for specialized genetic counselling and testing. Targeted next-generation sequencing (NGS) was applied. Sanger sequencing was used to confirm the candidate variant. Modelling was performed using the SWISS-MODEL server. RESULTS: A homozygous stop-gain variant c.**829G > T** (p.E277*) was found in the ATM gene. This variant was confirmed by Sanger sequencing and modelling of native structure, and truncated structure was performed. CONCLUSION: To date, very few pathogenic variants of the ATM gene have been reported from the Iranian population. The finding has implications in molecular diagnostic for A-T in Iran.",
                        "mention_type": "clinical",
                        "claim": "supports pathogenicity"
                    }
                ],
